fields.name: Basics
fields.theory: Georgian is the official language of Georgia and is spoken by approximately 3.7 million people. Georgian is one of the oldest languages in the world, and its literary tradition dates back to the 5th century.

fields.name: Basic Verbs
fields.description: I want, I eat, I know
fields.theory:
Georgian has a subject-verb-object primary sentence structure, but the word order is not as strict as in English. Subject can be omitted when it is mutually understood, like in Spanish.
For example, if you want an ice cream, you could say "( I ) ice cream want". As a rule, to say "I do smth", you add сГХ (v) to the beginning of a verb stem, like сГХсГнсГРсГЫ (I eat), сГХсГШсГксГШ (I know), сГХсГмсГФсГа (I write).
The particle сГРсГа is used to indicate simple negation. "I don't want" is "сГРсГа сГЫсГШсГЬсГУсГР" (ar minda).

fields.name: Alphabet
fields.theory: Georgian's alphabet consists of 33 letters. The script doesn't have capital letters. In Georgian, each letter is pronounce, letter pronunciation is always the same.
